	<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Hearing Tests</h2>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Can I test my hearing at home?">
			<p>
				Online tools and apps can be a helpful way to get a general sense
				of your hearing, but they can't take the place of a comprehensive
				evaluation with an audiologist. A professional hearing test allows
				us to truly understand what you're experiencing, confirm whether
				hearing loss is present, and identify the type and degree of any
				changes.
			</p>
			<p>
				It's also important to know that factors like earwax buildup or a
				blockage in the ear canal can temporarily affect your hearing and
				influence test results. This is something that can only be
				identified through a physical examination of the ear, which is an
				essential part of an in-person evaluation.
			</p>
			<p>
				In-person testing gives us the opportunity to look at the full
				picture of your hearing health and talk through your concerns in a
				way an online screen simply can't provide.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Are hearing tests safe?">
			<p>
				Yes, hearing tests are completely safe, painless, and non-invasive.
				There's nothing uncomfortable about the process. Most patients are
				surprised by how simple and relaxed the appointment feels. Our goal
				is to make you feel at ease from the moment you walk in.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Are online hearing tests reliable?">
			<p>
				Online hearing tests can give you a general sense of how you may be
				hearing, but they don't provide the precision needed for a true
				diagnosis. They also can't account for important factors like
				earwax, equipment differences, or your specific listening
				environment. Only an audiologist can accurately measure your
				hearing levels and determine the type and possible cause of any
				hearing loss, which is essential for the right treatment.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can I take a hearing test on my phone?">
			<p>
				Phone apps can be a convenient way to screen for potential hearing
				concerns, especially if you're just starting to notice changes.
				However, they should never replace a full evaluation. For accurate
				results—and to understand what's really going on with your
				hearing, a professional in-office test is strongly recommended.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="How often should I have my hearing tested?">
			<p>
				If your hearing is normal and you're not noticing any changes, a
				hearing test every 3–5 years is usually sufficient. If you already
				have hearing loss, wear hearing aids, or are regularly exposed to
				loud environments, we recommend checking your hearing annually.
				Regular visits help us catch even small changes early so we can
				adjust your care and keep you hearing your best.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

